 For a raw take on what it feels like to miss out on all of that upside, gi=
ve it a listen:=C2=A0
High Costs of Exercising
It can be really, really expensive to exercise your options. That=E2=80=99s=
 because there are two costs when it comes to exercising: the direct cost a=
nd the tax bill.=C2=A0
The direct cost is straightforward. You own 50k options at $1, you pay $50k=
 for the shares. That=E2=80=99s a lot of money, but ideally you=E2=80=99re =
doing it because you believe that what you=E2=80=99re buying is worth a lot=
 more. Let=E2=80=99s say, for example, that the company was recently valued=
 at $100 per share Nice! Free money!=C2=A0
Well=E2=80=A6 that=E2=80=99s where the tax bill comes in. According to Secf=
i=E2=80=99s research across 69 late-stage unicorn companies (companies valu=
ed at more than $1 billion), taxes make up 85% of the cost of exercising st=
ock options. =F0=9F=A4=AE
Since most people are unaware they=E2=80=99re going to have to pay taxes, S=
ecfi calls it the surprise factor. They call the overall expense the unaffo=
rdability factor.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve seen this firsthand (unfortunately, I haven=E2=80=99t felt it =
firsthand, but close enough).
At Breather, I worked with an ex-Uber employee who needed to exercise his o=
ptions within 90 days of leaving Uber to join Breather. He was early at Ube=
r and left when they were worth $10s of billions of dollars. Pretty amazing=
, right? Not so fast. Exercising meant he owed hundreds of thousands of dol=
lars in taxes, even though Uber wouldn=E2=80=99t IPO for another two years.=
=C2=A0
He couldn=E2=80=99t sleep because of the tax bill hanging over his head. He=
 spent the better portion of a few months on calls with people he was tryin=
g to sell shares to in order to generate the cash he needed to buy his opti=
ons. He asked me if I had any friends who might want to buy. Finally, he wa=
s able to find some people to buy some of his shares in the secondary marke=
t and used the proceeds to pay off the tax bill, but that meant giving up h=
is hard-earned upside after months of stress.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s easy to dismiss that as a Champagne problem, but it really suc=
ks. Upside is what your startup promised you, and why you took a pay cut in=
 the first place. Try choosing between owing the IRS hundreds of thousands =
or giving up equity you earned from years of grueling work. Uber was not kn=
own for its work/life balance.=C2=A0
Luckily, he was able to figure it out, and he did really well when Uber IPO=
=E2=80=99d (as did the people who bought his secondary).=C2=A0
Selling some of your shares to cover the tax bill is just one way to exerci=
se options. Let=E2=80=99s go over the full menu.
