=2E625em 0;"><strong>High Costs of Exerc=
ising</strong></h3><p style=3D"color:=
 #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It can be=
 really, really expensive to exercise your options. That&#8217;s because th=
ere are two costs when it comes to exercising: the <strong>direct cost</str=
ong> and the <strong>tax bill</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The direct cost i=
s straightforward. You own 50k options at $1, you pay $50k for the shares. =
That&#8217;s a lot of money, but ideally you&#8217;re doing it because you =
believe that what you&#8217;re buying is worth a lot more. Let&#8217;s say,=
 for example, that the company was recently valued at $100 per share Nice! =
Free money!&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Well&#8230; that&#8217;s where the tax bill c=
omes in. According to Secfi&#8217;s research across 69 late-stage unicorn c=
ompanies (companies valued at more than $1 billion), taxes make up 85% of t=
he cost of exercising stock options. &#129326;</p><div class=3D"captioned-i=
